<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="315" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,702,402,424]" box="[151,702,402,424]" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">
Type species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Banks, 1912: 179" authorityName="Banks" authorityPageNumber="179" authorityYear="1912" box="[294,698,402,424]" class="Insecta" family="Mantispidae" genus="Mantispilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="315" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulchella">
<emphasis box="[294,511,402,424]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">Mantispilla pulchella</emphasis>
Banks, 1912: 179
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,469,854]" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoffman" authorityYear="2002" box="[286,452,470,493]" class="Insecta" family="Mantispidae" genus="Leptomantispa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="315" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[286,452,470,493]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">Leptomantispa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is scarcely collected and very uncommon in museums. Species of this genus are apparently arboreal, and are likely difficult to collect. Perhaps the best way to collect specimens is by light traps. Until now the genus is composed of nine valid species occurring from southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[1096,1180,541,566]" name="Canada" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">Canada</collectingCountry>
to northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1318,1432,541,566]" name="Argentina" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, including the Antilles (
<bibRefCitation box="[408,517,577,602]" pageId="20" pageNumber="315" refId="ref18331" refString="Ohl, M. (2004) Annotated catalog of the Mantispidae of the world (Neuroptera). Contributions on Entomology, International, 5 (3), 131 - 262." type="journal article">Ohl 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[529,808,577,602]" pageId="20" pageNumber="315" refId="ref17864" refString="Machado, R. J. P. &amp; Rafael, J. A. (2010) Taxonomy of the Brazilian species previously placed in Mantispa Illiger, 1798 (Neuroptera: Mantispidae), with the description of three new species. Zootaxa, 2454, 3 - 59." type="journal article">Machado &amp; Rafael 2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[819,1182,577,602]" pageId="20" pageNumber="315" refId="ref16776" refString="Ardila-Camacho, A. &amp; Garcia, A. (2015) Mantidflies of Colombia (Neuroptera, Mantispidae). Zootaxa, 3937 (3), 401 - 455. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3937.3.1" type="journal article">Ardila-Camacho &amp; García 2015</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[1194,1425,577,602]" pageId="20" pageNumber="315" refId="ref17516" refString="Hoffman, K. M., Flint, O. S. Jr. &amp; Perez-Gelabert, D. E. (2017) The Mantispidae of the West Indies with special reference to the Dominican Republic (Neuroptera: Mantispidae). Insecta Mundi, 0 559, 1 - 15." type="journal article">
Hoffman 
<emphasis box="[1301,1349,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
). From 
<collectingCountry box="[226,336,613,638]" name="Colombia" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">Colombia</collectingCountry>
only one species has been reported, 
<taxonomicName authority="Ardila-Camacho" authorityName="Ardila-Camacho" authorityYear="2015" box="[801,1140,613,638]" class="Insecta" family="Mantispidae" genus="Leptomantispa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="315" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoffmani">
<emphasis box="[801,938,613,638]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">L. hoffmani</emphasis>
Ardila-Camacho
</taxonomicName>
from the department of 
<collectingRegion box="[151,261,649,674]" country="Colombia" name="Risaralda" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">Risaralda</collectingRegion>
. The genus can be distinguished because the presence of numerous fine setae on the entire dorsal surface of the pronotum, arising flush with the pronotal surface; body color pattern consisting in mixtures of yellow and brown; male abdominal tergites 4 and 5 and sometimes 3, bearing pores; male ectoproct with ventromedial lobe not sclerotized; gonarcal membrane without scales. Female spermatheca widening distally (
<bibRefCitation box="[1148,1319,757,782]" pageId="20" pageNumber="315" refId="ref17407" refString="Hoffman, K. M. (2002) Family Mantispidae. In Penny, N. D. (ed.), A guide to the lacewings (Neuroptera) of Costa Rica. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, 53 (12), 251 - 275." type="journal article">Hoffman 2002</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation pageId="20" pageNumber="315" refId="ref17864" refString="Machado, R. J. P. &amp; Rafael, J. A. (2010) Taxonomy of the Brazilian species previously placed in Mantispa Illiger, 1798 (Neuroptera: Mantispidae), with the description of three new species. Zootaxa, 2454, 3 - 59." type="journal article">Machado &amp; Rafael 2010</bibRefCitation>
). Here we reported the second species from 
<collectingCountry box="[873,986,793,818]" name="Colombia" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Navas)" authorityName="Navas" baseAuthorityName="Navas" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[1004,1236,793,818]" class="Insecta" family="Mantispidae" genus="Leptomantispa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="315" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="axillaris">
<emphasis box="[1004,1132,793,818]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">L. axillaris</emphasis>
(Navás)
</taxonomicName>
, collected in the departments of 
<collectingRegion box="[325,437,829,854]" country="Colombia" name="Antioquia" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">Antioquia</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[491,555,830,854]" country="Colombia" name="Sucre" pageId="20" pageNumber="315">Sucre</collectingRegion>
in the norther part of the country.
</paragraph>
